Let’s simplify **`git reset`** in very easy, real-life language 👇

***

# ✅ Git Reset (Simple Explanation)

👉 **Git reset means:**

> “Go back to an earlier point and undo changes”

***

## 🧠 Imagine This:

You made 3 commits:

```
Commit 1 → Commit 2 → Commit 3 (current)
```

Now you want to go back to **Commit 2**

👉 You use:

```bash
git reset HEAD~1
```

***

# ✅ What actually happens?

It depends on **which type of reset you use**

***

# 🔹 1. Soft Reset (safe)

👉 Only removes the commit  
👉 Keeps your changes

```bash
git reset --soft HEAD~1
```

### 🧠 Simple meaning:

❌ Commit deleted  
✅ Code still there (staged)

***

### ✅ Use:

“I just want to redo my last commit”

***

***

# 🔹 2. Mixed Reset (default ✅)

👉 Removes commit + unstages changes  
👉 Keeps code

```bash
git reset HEAD~1
```

### 🧠 Simple meaning:

❌ Commit deleted  
❌ Not staged anymore  
✅ Code still in files

***

### ✅ Use:

“I want to re-add files properly”

***

***

# 🔹 3. Hard Reset ⚠️

👉 Deletes everything

```bash
git reset --hard HEAD~1
```

### 🧠 Simple meaning:

❌ Commit deleted  
❌ Staging deleted  
❌ Code also gone

***

### ⚠️ Use:

“I want to completely discard everything”

***

***

# 🔥 Super Simple Table

| Command             | Commit    | Code (files) | Safe?        |
| ------------------- | --------- | ------------ | ------------ |
| `--soft`            | ❌ removed | ✅ kept       | ✅ Safe       |
| `--mixed` (default) | ❌ removed | ✅ kept       | ✅ Safe       |
| `--hard`            | ❌ removed | ❌ deleted    | ⚠️ Dangerous |

***

***

# ✅ Real DevOps Example

👉 You did wrong commit:

```bash
git commit -m "wrong change"
```

👉 Fix it:

```bash
git reset HEAD~1
```

Now:

* Code is still there ✅
* You can fix and commit again ✅

***

***

# 🧠 One-line (Very Easy)

> **git reset is used to undo commits and go back to a previous state, with options to keep or delete your changes.**

